post_text: Well as we wrap up our first week, here at JCS, we are so thankful for everyone who has worked so hard to make this happen. From the parents, to the students, to the community and to all of the staff at JCS - we want to say GREAT JOB!! We have proven that we are ready to face the year with "Patience, Flexibility and Grace". Mostly we have proven what it takes to be an EAGLE and we are all up for the task!! In the past we have unofficially considered Thursdays to be Eagle Pride day. Starting next Thursday, let's wear our BLUE and GOLD and celebrate what it means to be an Eagle....because every day is a "Great Day to be an Eagle"!!

post_text: Coming up tomorrow (8/25) and Wednesday 8/26! If you would like to bring child’s school supplies (K-6) feel free. Report directly to assigned homeroom or location and please enter the door that is allocated for your student’s grade. Wear your mask/shield and please practice social distancing – our new normal. We know that many of you have students in more than one grade so the recommendation is to attend the grade you feel you need to go to the most and, divide and conquer with your spouse, friend, grandparent, etc. We hope to video every homeroom/grade level meeting so if you cannot get around to all of your kids’ classrooms or just cannot make it that night you can still view the information. The teachers are back on campus starting tomorrow, so feel free to call, email, or text any of us and we will be happy to help. For Online learners there will be a meeting for parents on 8/31. K-6 @5:00 - 6:00, 7-12 6:00 - 7:00. This meeting will be virtual and you will receive a link to your email to participate. Stay tuned for more information.

post_text: Joseph Charter School would just like to say that we apologize for any inconvenience of today’s graduation. We were under the assumption that being in Phase II would allow us to have more people attend graduation. We were told yesterday afternoon that the guidelines for graduation have not changed to reflect Phase II reopening as of this moment. The state is working on new guidelines to reflect Phase II, but are not done yet. If they change before 4 pm we will definitely change quickly to reflect the new changes. We have limited space to park by the football field and we are saving those spots for family that have to be in their vehicles. We again apologize. We want to make this day a special day for our seniors as they have meant so much to our school. We would love to have anyone who would like to celebrate our seniors join us downtown as they drive through town at approximately after graduation has concluded. If you are set up downtown by 4:30 you should be safe. We will be streaming graduation live on Facebook starting at 4:00 pm.

In honor of our senior students, the Wallowa County schools will be turning on their football lights as a symbol of hope and support for all Wallowa County high school students beginning on Monday 4/13/2020

We want all of our students and especially our seniors to know how important they are to us and we care for each and every one of them.

The lights in Wallowa, Joseph and Enterprise will come on every Monday through the end of the school year at 20:20 military time in honor of our seniors (8:20 pm) and will light up the stadium for one minute of each school day lost during this pandemic.

By order of the Governor and our continued efforts to do our part to keep our community, our students and families safe from threat of COVID-19, Joseph School District and its properties are closed through April 28, 2020. This includes all facilities, sporting fields, playground areas and use of gym space. Joseph School District continues to work alongside and support our local and state leaders in this fight.

State Conventions - FCCLA, FBLA, FFA
District Band & Choir
All middle school basketball contests
All high school sports contests. Sports teams will continue to practice, but remember if you are not at school you can not practice."

Chelcee Mansfield is with Kendall Hough Hayes.
February 20 at 3:03 AM ·

Culinary and Food Science had the awesome opportunity to tour and learn from a local chocolatier today! We learned about cacao farming and processing, chemistry, marking (we all learned how to do a special mark for our own chocolates), and much more.
Thank you Arrowhead Chocolates for today! We sincerely enjoyed our time with you all, we learned a lot, and our own truffles were the perfect conclusion to a great lesson.

post_text: We are so excited to get our grades K-4 moved back into their classrooms in Joseph. Tomorrow the teachers will work to pack up their temporary classrooms at the ESD building and get settled back into their regular classrooms. K-4 will be back in their classrooms in Joseph - starting Monday, February 10. Busses will be back to their normal routes, lunch will continue to be served at the community center (busses will transport kids there and back). We want to thank everyone for their support!

post_text:
Our library took on a lot of smoke damage. Insurance will be replacing the books and it will be a long and arduous task to get the library back up and running again. In the interim, please consider donating to this Donors Choose project . We have gone through and chosen a small selection of books that will especially cater to our K-4 students. These books will be used for classroom reading towards their Accelerated Reading goals, which are part of their daily curriculum. Once we get up to our goal of $597, it will automatically ship these books and we can use them to get started over the next couple of weeks. If you donate within the next 6 days, your donation will be doubled up to $50 with the code LIFTOFF. It's a great day to be an EAGLE, or in this case a PHOENIX - as we rise from the ashes!

https://www.donorschoose.org/project/the-pheonix-library-project-rising-fro/4750826/?rf=email-system-2020-01-project_submitted-teacher_7084949&challengeid=21552881&utm_swu=2457&utm_source=dc&utm_medium=page&utm_campaign=ifproject&utm_term=teacher_7084949

post_text: Wonderful! Thank you Helix Grizzlies!! 💚💛🐻
shared_text:
Helix School District
January 22 at 2:31 AM ·

As many of you know, the Joseph School District had a devastating fire in their gymnasium last week. Fire and water damaged a large portion of their elementary school, cafeteria, hallways and gym. The Helix School District will be holding a fundraiser during the Saturday, Jan. 25th basketball game against Powder Valley. As is always the case, admission to the game is free, but a cake raffle will be held and admission donations will be accepted. At the start of the girls’ and boys’ varsity games, we will be “Passing the Hat” to solicit additional donations. In addition, the Helix Booster Club has graciously agreed to match the total dollar amount raised at this event.

The Helix School District will present a check to Superintendent and girls’ basketball coach Lance Homan at the home basketball game against Joseph on Friday, January 31st. For more information, please contact the Helix School District office at (541) 457-2175.

post_text: Some tips for cleaning those smoke filled back packs and clothes. Have a tip? ⬇️Drop it here⬇️
shared_text:
Jeni Greenshields
January 21 at 8:50 AM ·

Joseph Parents dealing with smoke damaged clothes/shoes/backpacks...I have been working on this all day times three boys! Finally success! I soaked everything in hot water with 1 Cup White Vinegar and 1 Cup Baking Soda (or 2 of each when I used the bathtub) for an hour or so. Then I washed them with hot water, detergent, fabric softener, AND Oxi Clean TWICE. (NOTE: I tried just washing them without soaking them, but the smell still gave me a headache).

post_text: ***edit to add we could use a couple small bookshelves for a while : email angela.gorham@staff.josephcharter.org if you can help ****It may be a couple weeks, it may be longer. Until we know let's help our kids "keep their brains smart". The Joseph Eagle welcomes his friend the Pheonix to help us as we rebuild. We are accepting book donations for our temporary "Phoenix Library" as we "rise from the ashes". We are especially looking for the early reader-type books for 1-3 grades, but are accepting books for K-6. If you have gently used books that you would like to donate, please drop them off at the Blythe Cricket in Joseph or Building Healthy Families in Enterprise. If you would like to donate money to purchase books that will remain in the library once we rebuild, stay tuned for a GoFundMe account being created for this purpose. It's a GREAT day to be an EAGLE!

post_text: Thank you Flannel Lantern ❤️
shared_text:
The Flannel Lantern
January 19 at 7:35 PM ·

🍀Good morning! The sun is shining and Connor McGregor is the champ again!!! It’s a great day!!!

We all know retail therapy is a thing....especially when we’re feeling down. Next week while the school is closed, I am going to offer ALL Joseph Charter Students & Staff 30% OFF their purchase. It’s going to be a long week for the kids while mom and dad are at work. If you need them to have a parent to touch base with while you’re at work you know I’m here.

⏰I’m going to be OPEN tomorrow for the holiday 11-4.

I’m so in love with how this community comes together in time of need. Joseph Charter shaped our son into the man he is today and we are forever grateful and indebted to their staff. 💛💙💛💙💛💙

Tonight, our Community Center was used to reunite friends, reunite staff with students, provide an opportunity to connect staff and students with counseling, and to connect seekers of information with a few answers. January 17, 7:18 pm - A K-12 staff meeting was held this morning and it was decided that we will not be prepared for students next week. Joseph Charter School will be closed for students next week (January 20th - 24th). The staff will work to regroup and prepare to make the best plan to get the kids back in school by Monday 1/27. We thank everyone for all of the continued support as we move forward. We will keep everyone updated as the plan comes together for the following week.

Please avoid coming up to the school as emergency vehicles are in route.

We want to let all parents and community members know that there has been a report that an older gentleman tried to pick up a couple of students after school today while they were walking home. We are contacting law enforcement and will make sure adults are out and about after school. Please share!! We want our kids to be safe and we will do everything we can to make that happen.
If you notice anything strange, or have any information on this situation please contact Lance Homan, or Sherri Kilgore right away.

Chelcee Mansfield is with Dakota DeLyria.

It has been a whirlwind few weeks! From ag sales (congratulation to our beginning team earning 1st place!! And our incredible advanced members doing a great job in job interview), to gingerbread home building, hearing from some stellar women in our community (Blithe Cricket owners during CAP classes & our own Joseph, Oregon mayor Teresa Logosz-Sajonia) and making Grinch popcorn with Mrs. Grover’s class, it’s been an awesome few weeks.
Last night we had our staff Christmas party at Vali’s, the food was Divine! Zach and I laughed way too much and had a really nice evening.
I hope everyone enjoys a restful and celebratory Christmas break!

post_text: This week! There is still time to bring in your gently used books for the book exchange ❤️
shared_text:
Joseph Charter School
December 5, 2019 at 8:11 PM ·

This year the JCS will continue the holiday tradition. We will be having a Jolabokaflod (slightly modified). This is a lovely Icelandic tradition (Christmas Book Flood) a day of giving books on December 24 and spending the day snuggled and reading. For JCS we will have a Jolabokaflod Book Swap and will collect books next week (December 9th-12th) in the library. We are NOT collecting new books, but gently used books in good condition that are ready for a new home :)For each book a student brings, they will receive a ticket to use towards their own "new" book (all children will receive at least one book)Then on December 24th they will hopefully have a "new" book to snuggle up and read with their families! The book swap will take place on Wednesday and Thursday Dec. 18-19 during library time. Grades K-6th are invited to participate Happy Reading!

Wallowa County Chieftain
October 4, 2019 at 6:32 PM ·

Joseph ran away with the girls Joseph-Pine Eagle volleyball match on Thursday evening, winning all three games by big margins. P-E played well in game 2, with the lead changing several times. Game 3 was close until Pine-Eagle had scored 6 points, but then Joseph took control.

Score: 25-8, 25-17, 25-8

Photos:
Volleyball cutlines
1. Joseph’s Molly Curry blocks a return from Pine Eagle’s Marti Lopez in the first game.

5. Joseph’s Sabrina Albee unleashes a slam over Pine Eagle’s Jodi Graven in the first game.

20. Savannah Simpson and Maddie Morgan go for the dig together in the third game.

22. Joseph’s Sabrina Albee slams the ball past Pine Eagle’s Maddie Morgan late in game 3

post_text:
Spread the word! The application for Girls in Science 2019 is NOW OPEN!

.

If you know a 6th-8th grade girl in Eastern Oregon who loves all things STEM, this is the opportunity for them!

.

The program will be held at Eastern Oregon University in La Grande on Saturday, October 26th, featuring the theme, "Zombie Apocalypse: Is It Actually Possible?" Students will put their chemistry, biology, math, and computer science skills to work to solve an engaging biomedical mystery.

.

Only 100 spaces are available! Refer to the flyer and online application for all details.

.

The $10 application fee provides admitted students with lunch, a t-shirt, and all supplies for the day. It will be refunded if a student is not selected to attend.

.

Hurry! The online application closes on Friday, October 4th.

post_text: Mr. Koehn was recently awarded Oregon Agriculture Teacher’s Association Outstanding Agriculture Educator 💙🦅💛 Congrats, Toby!
text: Mr. Koehn was recently awarded Oregon Agriculture Teacher’s Association Outstanding Agriculture Educator 💙🦅💛 Congrats, Toby!

post_text: We would also like to welcome Mrs. Mansfield to our team! She grew up in Wallowa County where she fostered a love for agriculture, education, community, and the great outdoors. Her mom, dad and sisters instilled the importance of a good work ethic and inspired her to be a part of FFA, 4-H, sports, National Honor Society, FCCLA, horseback riding, Chief Joseph Days and so much more. She served as an Oregon FFA State Officer and then graduated from Oregon State University with a Bachelor of Science in Animal Science and a Master of Science in Agriculture Education. She spent two years with Echo School District and has spent the last six years at Union School District. She brings with her an incredible husband and two sweet little girls who are very excited to move home to their cousins. This county has always had their hearts and the opportunity to live and work here is a dream come true for them. We are all so excited! 💙

post_text: We would like to welcome Jennifer Littlepage to our team! She will be the new Joseph Charter School Secretary 😀 She is married and has two children, on of which is currently a JCS Eagle. She enjoys spending time with her family and friends, baking, crafting and hiking. Before moving from the coast to Joseph last summer, she worked at Jewell School District for 9 years. We are so excited to have her 💙🎉

post_text: We would like to welcome Ms. Weaver to our team! Ms. Weaver was raised in Wallowa, Oregon where she attended high school. After earning her Masters from EOU, Weaver began working at Wallowa School District as a grade 7-12 English teacher. Ms. Weaver currently resides in Enterprise and is excited to be a part of the Joseph Charter team this fall. She spends her summers fighting fire for Oregon Department of Forestry. Her spare time is spent hiking, writing, skiing, volunteering on the Enterprise City Fire Department, and studying to get her EMT certification. We are so excited to have her! 🎉💙

Wallowa County Chieftain
April 29, 2019 at 7:27 AM ·

Joseph Charter School seniors, Ella Coughlan and Tyler Homan impressed at Saturday's Joseph track meet.

Homan's name now tops the schools record books in the 300 meter Hurdles. It's said that Homan outpaced the field, finishing nearly 30 yards ahead of his closest rival.

Ella Coughlan shattered the meet's previous record of 2:29 with a stunning 2:26 in the 800 meter race.

Please, join the Wallowa County Chieftain in congratulating these fine student athletes!

Photo credit: Left: Kana Oliver
Right: Ellen Morris Bishop

post_text:
Real Talk: A Honest Conversation about Substance Use
April 29
6-7:30pm
Tomas Conference Room in Enterprise

Join us as we explore the current dynamics of substance use, prevention, adolescence, and family life with guest speaker Matt Vogel. We will look at specific substances, health impacts, trends, and skill-building that will have positive impacts in our homes and community. This seminar is relevant for professionals in any human service field, parents, and interested community members.

Matt Vogel lives in southern Oregon and worked in higher education for 16 years in both teaching and administrative capacities. He is a sought-after speaker on a variety of health related topics; one of his specialty areas being the topic of substance use. He regularly presents at conferences, universities, high schools, and community coalitions.

Free and open to the public.

For more information, contact 541-426-4524 x1031.

Joseph Charter School had a very successful battle of the books just before Spring Break! All of the teams did a great job! The overall winners of the 4th-6th grade competition on the book "Dragon's Milk" by Susan Fletcher were the 4th grade "Off the Page Readers", composed of Hans Rowden, Olivia DeMelo and Madison Schave. We would like to thank everyone who contributed to the battle and especially Jacob Losby for being an awesome MC, BoDean Warnock for always being the score keeper and judge, The Imnaha grandmas and Shari Warnock for preparing our chili for the feed, Joseph Education Foundation for providing the wonderful books, The Big Read and Cam Scott for collaborating with us and providing the Dragon's Milk book and Christine Eaves and Maria Weer for food donations.

Click the link below for some fun photos from the night 😀

Submit photos March 1 - March 23, 2019

Submit digital photos online at: https://wallowaphotocontest.org/. There is an adult division and a student division.

post_text: Mrs. Grover's third grade class participated in a read-a-thon as part of Ellyse Tingelstad's FCCLA project. Elly is raising money for a thirteen-year-old girl who lives in Western Oregon and has Hodgkin's Lymphoma. This young girl is currently undergoing intense treatment. With this being said, Elly recruited the third graders to help raise money to donate to this young girl and her family. Before the read-a-thon she taught the kids about illnesses, and gave a lesson on the importance of helping others throughout difficult times. The read-a-thon was very successful, the students read 220 books altogether, and raised over $700!

Welcome to the 3rd annual Joseph Charter School battle of the Books competition! Students have been reading novels in class and will create teams to compete against each other in an academic challenge of comprehension. Grades 2nd-6th will participate. There will also be a very special battle between the 4th-6th grade classes using the novel “Dragon’s Milk” by Susan Fletcher. This is in partnership with The Big Read. We hope your child will be able to join us! All students are welcome, whether they are participating or part of the audience.

While there is not cost for your child to join, there will be a fundraiser chili feed on March 21st to help with continuing to purchase books for our school/classrooms that your family is invited to attend. The cost is $5.00 per person or $10 per family.
